<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-858-748  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 858 748.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>CommunicationsWeek  Nov 6 1989 n273 p57(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Back-to-school time for equipment distributors. (CommunicationsBusiness Closeup)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Wilde, Candee.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>As the computer and communications equipment sold by variousvendors becomes more standardized and similar in features andprocessing capability, distribution management and marketingstrategy become increasingly important.andP;  The sales force must beprepared to help customers develop solutions and the applicationsthat produce solutions.andP;  Prepurchase consultation and post-salesupport and service are an increasingly significant aspect of acompany's competitive performance.andP;  The three basic distributionchannels are direct sales, third-party distribution and retailoutlets.andP;  Companies such as Intel Corp, with no direct sales forceto go after the 29 million microcomputers in the marketplace,employ a creative type of '800' service that features an elaboratemenu-driven sales qualification program.andP;  Whatever strategy isdevised, educated selling is clearly an emerging trend.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Intel Corp. (marketing).andO;Ticker:    INTC.andO;Topic:     Communications EquipmentComputer IndustryCompetitionDistribution ManagementMarketing Strategy.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>